<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <title>The Living Treaty – Language & Translator</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css" />
</head>
<body>
  <header class="site-header">
    <div class="header-main">
      <div>
        <h1>The Living Treaty</h1>
        <p class="tagline">
          L’nui’suti and English in conversation – a small bridge between two worlds.
        </p>
      </div>
      <nav class="main-nav">
        <a href="index.html">Timeline</a>
        <a href="language.html">Language / Translator</a>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main class="layout">
    <section class="controls">
      <h2>Language as Worldview</h2>
      <p class="hint">
        This page is not a full dictionary. It’s a teaching tool built from a small
        basket of words and patterns you shared – like <code>-ji'j</code>
        diminutives, time words, and relational meanings.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="translator-layout">
      <section class="translator-panel">
        <h2>Mi’kmaw ↔ English bridge</h2>
        <p class="hint">
          Type a Mi’kmaw word (S/F.O or Listuguj) like
          <code>amu</code>, <code>amuji'j</code>, <code>tpuk</code>,
          <code>awnasiey</code>, <code>Netukulimk</code>,
          <code>Msit No'kmaq</code>,
          or an English gloss like <code>bee</code>, <code>winter</code>,
          <code>nervous</code>.
        </p>

        <div class="translator-input-row">
          <input
            id="bridge-input"
            type="text"
            placeholder="Enter a Mi’kmaw form or English meaning…"
            autocomplete="off"
          />
          <button id="bridge-button">Translate</button>
        </div>

        <div id="bridge-results" class="translator-results">
          <!-- bridge.js will fill this -->
        </div>
      </section>

      <aside class="translator-notes">
        <h2>How this bridge thinks</h2>
        <p>
          This translator does not try to perfectly convert between L’nui’suti and
          English. It follows a Two-Eyed Seeing approach:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Western eye:</strong> simple pattern rules (like recognizing
            <code>-ji'j</code> as a diminutive / child-form) and clear code structure.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>L’nuk eye:</strong> each entry has a relational explanation – what
            the word means in terms of kinship, land, spirit, and responsibility.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          If you are an Elder, language keeper, or learner: this is meant to support
          your work, not replace you. The basket of words and explanations should grow
          through community guidance.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </section>
  </main>

  <footer class="site-footer">
    <p>
      This page uses a very small Mi’kmaw lexicon and pattern rules. Any serious use
      should involve fluent speakers, Elders, and community custodians.
    </p>
  </footer>

  <script src="bridge.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
